In article <2nfpmi$cne@agate.berkeley.edu>,
Steve Pope <spp@bob.eecs.berkeley.edu> wrote:
>Another security aspect of PGP is vulnerability to spoofing.
>An adversary could spoof a sender by forging the message
>providing the public key, causing the sender to encrypt
>using the adversary's public key, rather than the 
>recipients.

That's why you should certify a key only if you received it
from the hands of its owner, and trust only keys certified
by people whose judgement you trust.
